 class=title> Racial Profiling....</span><hr size=1> Okay, given the recent events I was thinking about 2 issues that have come up.<br>
<br>
<font color=yellow>1.  Racial Profiling.</font color><br>
<br>
   I guess to some degree I don't understand the problem here.  I obviously don't support pulling people over or stopping them based on color.  That is a problem.<br>
<br>
   I have to ask, however, if you are pulled over based on color/race after something like September 11th... is it really that big of a deal.  To what extent do we encourage people not to do this.  Do we let people pass, despite suspicion of wrong doing, because we are afraid of being accused of profiling.<br>
<br>
   I don't know, part of me says that if a cop pulls over someone of middle eastern origin for a LEGITIMATE reason... and decides to run the guys ID where he normally wouldn't... I think that is justified.  I am NOT talking about seeing someone who looks foreign and pulling them over just to check their ID, nor am I talking about treating them like a criminal.  I am JUST talking about a cop who says to himself "I am gonna run this just in case."<br>
<br>
   I know, part of me says this is unfair to the individual... but then part of me is reminded that to error (if it is an error) on the side of caution is better than to have more incidents like this one.<br>
<br>
<font color=yellow>2.  Hate Crimes.</font color><br>
<br>
   I don't understand what a Hate Crime is.  I mean, I know how the government looks at it... but it makes no sense to me.<br>
<br>
   I assume that most violent crimes are enacted with a certain ammount of hatred, whether long term or short term.  As far as I am concerned you are violating a persons Constitutional rights by handing out different sentences for different people based on percieved situations.<br>
<br>
   Oh, you hated the ethnic origin of the person.. oh, well then lets double the sentence.  You called him a "nigger" while you were choking him, oh, then you get twice as tough a sentence as the man who killed a 8 year old girl.<br>
<br>
   Killing is killing, assault is assault.  If you want to toughen sentences accross the board, so be it... but I don't like this situational justice.  I think its important to point out that murder can fairly be distinguished from man slaughter in some cases and I am not talking about that.<br>
<br>
   To me it seems that hate crime legislation as well as affirmitive action are forcing people to focus on the very thing they claim to try and stamp out.<br>
<br>
   Under affirmative action an employer was forced to look at the color of the skin, to give a minority man/woman a job they MIGHT not have otherwise earned, just to meet a quota.<br>
<br>
   What purpose does hate crime legislation serve?  Does this mean that minorities, whether ethnic or otherwise, deserve swifter or more severe vengance?<br>
<br>
   I am curious, if you kill a man and he turns out to be gay... are you guilty of a hate crime.  Not in my eyes, but then... the court decides.<br>
<br>
   People might say, "It's not fair for them to be singled out for persecution."  Explain that to the parents of a straight child whose son was murdered, and the murderer got half the sentence that a convicted "hate crime murderer" got.  Do you think that the sexual preference of their child matters to them at this point?  Substitute race if you want, same question.<br>
<br>
   <br>
<br>
<font color=red><b>Note:<br>
  I don't have a solid opinion on either of these issues, despite what it may seem.  These are just questions in my mind.  Feel free to express your opinion.  I am sure some people will feel the need to "educate" me.</b></font color> <p><font color=green><b>Cendan Tankenpriest</b></font color><br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#E9D756>(1/8/02 1:17:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=262.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Racial Profiling....</span><hr size=1> Cendan, Let me educate you... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  J/K<br>
<br>
Concerning profiling:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;I don't know, part of me says that if a cop pulls over someone of middle eastern origin for a LEGITIMATE reason... and decides to run the guys ID where he normally wouldn't... I think that is justified.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The problem is over just what counts as a &quot;legitimate&quot; reason. Pulling someone over because of their ethnicity is not legitimate. One reason is that discrimination is apparent in profiling. Usually profiling is only accomplished with people of color. If 9/11 had been comitted by a German terrorist group, then we would not be able to &quot;profile&quot; in most cases because of skin color. That to me demonstrates a glaring problem with profiling. It is usually just a rationalization for outright discrimination on the basis of race and religion. For instance, how does one tell if a person is of Middle Eastern origin? There are &quot;white&quot; people born in the Middle East who are Christians. Do we pull over people who are brown and carry the Koran, for instance? Again, what would count as &quot;legitimate&quot;?<br>
<br>
Conerning hate crimes:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;To me it seems that hate crime legislation as well as affirmitive action are forcing people to focus on the very thing they claim to try and stamp out.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The FBI defines hate crimes as &quot;a criminal offense committed against a person, property or society which is motivated, in whole or in part, by the offender's bias against a race, religion, disability, sexual orientatio, or ethnicity/national origin.&quot; &lt;<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fbi.gov/ucr/Cius_98/98crime/98cius16.pdf>">www.fbi.gov/ucr/Cius_98/9...ius16.pdf></a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
It is the nature of such a crime that distinguishes it from all other types of crimes. Hence, punishment suitable to the nature of the crime must be enforced upon offenders. It is not difficult to discern from the above definition why hate crimes are unique and should be treated seperately under the law. The sort of malice involved in a hate crime is worthy the contempt of a humane society and offenders should be treated with extreme prejudice, I think.<br>
<br>
The difficulty may be in ascertaining whether or not a hate crime has been commited. A black man butchered in his home with a burning cross in the front yard is clearly a hate crime. A gay man gunned down in the street with no clear indication that he was shot because he was gay is going to be a tough case. However, in those cases where a hate crime is clearly commited punishment should fit the nature of the malice.<br>
<br>
