<br>
1. Racial Profiling - Whether the cop wants to admit it or not, running a middle easterner's identity &quot;just in case&quot; is a form of (negative) discrimination.  There's no two ways about this.  I'm not saying that discrimination as an act of classifying people according to physical attributes is wrong, per se, but becomes wrong when you make connections between these attributes and an increased likelihood in criminal activity.  One might argue that certain ethnicities are more likely to have committed a crime simply through statistics, but this is not evidence of wrong-doing and should not be considered to even possibly to connect with a suspect.  <br>
<br>
Sure, perhaps the person pulled over committed a crime.  Depending on the type of crime an officer can or cannot legally search the individual, his/her car or his/her residence/office/whatever.  The legal precidents are in place in order to protect his/her rights, as well as everyone else's rights as free citizens.<br>
<br>
Lastly, and this is something I just LOVE bringing up, if we started running checks on Middle Easterners because of their possible (however unsubstantiated) ties to terrorist activities, why wouldn't these checks be performed on caucasians? There was an American Taliban you know. Further, why weren't white people given such scrutiny after Timothy McVeigh's attack on the Federal Building in Kansas City? <br>
<br>
Just an interesting figure as well: About 1 in 20 foreign students studying in the US has been arrested, detained or questioned in regards to terrorism.  <br>
<br>
Sorry Cen, profiling is clear-cut discrimination in my mind.<br>
<br>
2. Hate Crimes<br>
<br>
The use of the term Hate Crime is only applied if it's found that the violent act committed was due to a conscious and premeditated hatred toward the individual based on ethnicity, sexual preference, or whatever other attribute where discrimination threatens a minority of individuals that the courts decide warrant protection. <br>
<br>
There's a reason for this. These demographics are the minority.  The intent is to attempt to protect minorities, to give them the same liberties that the 'majority' holds.  The majority may be the Catholics, the Whites, the Heterosexuals, or just the opposite (in my mind) if someone attacks, kills or threatens a person who is in the minority in a situation where the majority could pose a serious hamper on his/her liberty.  <br>
<br>
In the end, to me (as well as you, I gather) for a crime to be a Hate Crime, hatred due to prejudice against the person must be proven.  This goes without qualifying what prejudice is, and yes, the courts decide the standards by which this is all determined, but I cannot say that removing system in place for &quot;Hate Crimes&quot; will help anything.  I think it would hurt the situations, honestly, but can you honestly tell me this is wrong:<br>
<br>
A man walks into a bar.  He's with friends, also male, who know that he is homosexual.  The bar is predominantly heterosexual.  This man obviously knows this, and assuming he's in his right mind, he feels no need to broadcast that he's gay.  One of his friends, after a few drinks, jokes with him, asking if he finds such and such a guy &quot;cute&quot;.  Someone, let's say a guy named Bert, near them overhears, and with a few drinks in him, and while the gay man tries to difuse his joking friend, Bert flips out, beats the man senseless.  At sentencing it's found this is a hate crime.  The judge imposes a longer sentence than for a normal bar-room altercation, let's say, in accordance with hate crime laws in the state of x.  Bert is being punished not only for the beating, but for harboring views that are intolerable to society (as seen by the courts) because they infringe on the gay man's liberty.  <br>
<br>
I'm rather sure this is how Hate Crime law is supposed to work, and I think that's great.  You can't just go beat someone because they're gay.  You want to argue the finer points of the statutes.  I'd rather let the statutes stand up against a court system that has the ability to change itself through precident and appeal.  <br>
<br>
