Ah, right, got it. &quot;Legitimate&quot; here being something like pulling a car over with a tail light out. But, since that is the case then what could &quot;profiling&quot; mean? If I am stopping someone for a legitimate reason, then I am not really profiling them, right? I am going to run a check against their license plates and driver's license as a matter of procedure (most cops do). Now, of course, if I pull over a car for a broken tail light to find that the passenger is browned skin and wearing a Turban and decide to search the vehicle based upon those attributes of the driver, then I am profiling. However, that seems to be wrong to me. I would just be justifying racial prejudice or religious prejudice under the guise of profiling. Hmm... a perplexing issue you have raised. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
