<br>
I see your point. I think you are saying that hate is wrong, period and that punishing hate crime offenders (on the basis of criminal definitions of &quot;hate crime&quot;) only engenders more hate. Society is thereby &quot;hating&quot; the hate crime criminal and infliciting an unjust sentence upon them which is equally wrong. Something like that?<br>
<br>
If so the difficulty is one of equivocating on &quot;hate&quot;. Speaking for myself, I hate murder (I think many feel the same way). There are varying degrees of murder based upon the nature of the crime. The punishment met out to a murderer is not based upon one's hate for murder, but what is considered just (by society) punishment for the act. Accidentally capping a family member is not as culpable an act as premeditating the death of someone then executing the action that kills. Point being, that the punishments involved have nothing to do with the individual responsible, but the percieved severity of the act itself.<br>
<br>
Here we may find that a hate crime is even more blameworthy because not only did the individual probably premeditate the murder but did so on the basis of the victim's race, religion, sexual orientation, etc. Society has found that justice can only be served by punishing such crimes with extreme prejudice. As a society we want to differentiate between varying degrees of malice involved in the crime. &quot;Hate Crimes&quot; involve the greatest degree of malice. The desire to cause pain to another in such cases go far beyond simple hatred of the person, but a deep hatred of the person's spirit: their very identity. At any rate, I am starting to get preachy. Better stop here. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
